##Government spending on health is slowing, and the health care system is looking to boost spending

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

Meng Qingwei reporting from Beijing

Over the past 40 years of reform and opening-up, the scale of government health investment has been increasing year by year, and the average annual growth rate of government health investment has been outpacing the average annual growth rate of GDP.

Data from the National Institutes of Health's Center for Health Development Research show that government spending on health has been expanding since 2015, real growth in government spending on health started to slow: from 17.8% in 2015 to 4.8% in 2018.

"This is a major concern at the moment. In particular, China is now at a crucial stage of building a 'healthy China' , deepening healthcare reform and solving the problem of 'expensive medical care' . In accordance with the initiative goal of the World Health Organization's 'universal health coverage' , China is still in the process of providing adequate, stable and sustainable government health investment to support and safeguard health development, " said Zhang Yuhui, a researcher and deputy director of the Health Development Research Center of the National Health Commission, in an interview with the China business daily.

The Research Center for Health Development of the National Health and Health Commission is responsible for the accounting of total health expenditure, which carries out research on the prediction of total health expenditure, studies the scale and structure of health expenditure, and provides the basis for the decision-making of the central government departments.

Since the reform and opening up, with the rapid growth of the economy, China's government investment in health is also increasing. However, experts and health system officials said in the interview that government spending on health should be further increased, especially the establishment of a sustainable government input mechanism to provide policy guarantees for health input.

What kind of mechanism should be set up to ensure the sustainability of government health investment? Is it possible to link health spending to GDP in the same way that fiscal spending on education is no less than 4 per cent of GDP?

With the deepening reform of China's medical system and mechanism, the building of a "healthy China" has entered an important stage. In particular, the new pneumonia epidemic has put many aspects of China's medical and health system to the test, what kind of long-term mechanism of health investment is in front of our eyes.

"The level of government investment in health care is more reasonable. "

There are many indicators of health investment in a country.

Zhang Yuhui told reporters that the indicators commonly used internationally and officially used domestically to measure the level of national health investment include the total health expenditure and the total health expenditure per capita; the indicators reflecting the intensity of health investment can be divided into two categories, the proportion of total health expenditure to GDP (gross domestic product) can reflect the importance and investment level of the whole country and the whole society One is the proportion of the broad sense government expenditure on health (including government expenditure on health services and social security) in the broad sense government expenditure, which can reflect the strength of public funds in protecting the health of the population and the burden of seeking medical care, according to the domestic statistical classification, the commonly used analytical scope is the proportion of government health expenditure to fiscal expenditure.

The total health expenditure is mainly personal health expenditure except the general government health expenditure. Research shows that the higher the proportion of personal health expenditure in total health expenditure, the higher the risk of people suffering from catastrophic medical expenditure or returning to poverty due to illness. Therefore, it is necessary to increase the proportion of general government health expenditure, ease the economic burden of personal medical treatment.

China Business News reported from the National Health Commission's Health Development Research Center that in 2018, China's total health expenditure was 5,912.2 billion yuan, accounting for 6.4 percent of GDP. In terms of funding sources, according to the parallel approach adopted by our country, government expenditure on health, social health and personal health are 1,639.9 billion yuan, 2,581.1 billion yuan and 1,691.2 billion yuan respectively, the proportion of total health expenditure was 27.7% , 43.7% and 28.6% respectively. The proportion of personal health expenditure to total health expenditure is the lowest level in nearly 20 years.

"compared with international data, according to the latest statistics from the World Health Organization, our per capita GDP in 2017 was US $8,744.88 at the official exchange rate, ranking 75th among the 194 member countries of the World Health Organization; Total Health Expenditure per capita was us $560.42, ranking 71st; and Total Health Expenditure as a share of GDP was 6.43% , ranking 96th. From the perspective of financing security, China ranks 118th in the share of personal health expenditure among the member countries of the World Health Organization, and 104th in the share of general government health expenditure,"Zhang told reporters.

It is understood that since the reform and opening up, China's total health expenditure has increased year by year, but there is still a certain gap between developed countries. In 2016, the average health expenditure as a percentage of GDP in OECD countries was 9.1% , with 33 out of 36 countries having higher input levels than China.

At the end of 2018, Liu Kun, the Minister of Finance, revealed during an inquiry at the seventh session of the 13th Standing Committee of the National People's Congress that the level of health investment by the Chinese government was relatively reasonable. In 2015, according to calculations by the World Health Organization, in China, the proportion of general government expenditure on health is 59.8% .

"We believe that this proportion of input is appropriate to China's basic national conditions, " Liu said of the interpretation of the index.

Liu further explained that while the figure of 59.8 percent was still lower than that of developed countries such as the United Kingdom and Canada, it was higher than that of the brics countries such as Brazil and India, with 42.8 percent and India with 26.5 percent.

Liu also cited differences in the health care system to explain why the figure is valid in China. In the UK, where the National Health Insurance Scheme is in place, it is 80.4 per cent, he said, compared with 50.5 per cent in the US, where the private insurance scheme is in place. "China, as a country with a social medical insurance system, the current input level of 59.8 per cent is basically in line with the General Law. "

One reason is China's low fiscal spending as a share of GDP, at 24.6 per cent in 2017, well below the OECD average of more than 45 per cent. Liu Kun believes that in the government available financial proportion is low, the corresponding proportion of health care will be low. However, the fiscal expenditure on health has been increasing year by year, and the growth rate has continuously exceeded the growth level of the fiscal expenditure in the same period.

In recent years, the proportion of general government health expenditure to total health expenditure has been increasing in China, which was only 49.4% in 2009 and 55.89% in 2011, but lower than the global average.

"At present, this broad indicator is around 60 per cent, which is similar to the world average, " said Cai Jiangnan, founder and executive director of the Chuangqi Institute for Health Development in Shanghai, visiting professor at the china-europe Business School and former director of the Center for Health Management and policy at the china-europe business school.

Cai also told reporters that there is a more stringent international common indicator, is a country's financial health expenditure accounted for the proportion of total financial expenditure. According to the data published in 2017, the proportion of China's fiscal expenditure on health is 7.12% .

"This is the proportion of the total fiscal expenditure that comes directly from government finances, and the level in developed countries is generally around 20 per cent, compared to China, which is relatively low, " Cai said.

The growth rate of government health expenditure has fluctuated obviously in recent years

International Research shows that, on the one hand, with the economic growth, people will pay more and more attention to health, and the government will spend more and more on health.

On the other hand, with the increase of government investment in health, people's demand for health services will continue to be met, and the health status of the people will be improved, can Increase Labor capital, improve work efficiency, lengthen labor force working hours and so on, will further promote economic growth.

Since the reform and opening up, with the rapid growth of the economy, China's government investment in health is also increasing. In terms of scale, government expenditure on health increased from 3.5 billion yuan in 1978 to 1.6 trillion yuan in 2018, and its share of GDP increased from 0.96% in 1978 to 1.82% in 2018.

And from the speed of view, the government health expenditure growth rate also "outpaced" a number of economic indicators.

Zhang Yuhui told reporters that during this period, the average annual growth rate of government health investment was 11.2% , higher than the average annual growth rate of GDP (9.4%) and the average annual growth rate of fiscal expenditure (8.8%) , reflecting the importance the party and the government attach to the health cause.

Combing the data since the reform and opening up, the reporter found that in most years the growth rate of government health expenditure is higher than the GDP growth rate.

However, it is worth noting that in recent years, under the background of increasing downward pressure on the economy and increasingly prominent contradictions between fiscal revenue and expenditure, the growth rate of government expenditure on health has fluctuated obviously, especially in recent years, the growth rate has continued to slow down, and the real growth rate in 2015 was 17.8% , it fell to single digits in 2017 and continued to fall to 4.8 percent in 2018.

"This is the issue that needs to be focused on right now. In particular, China is now at a critical stage of building a 'healthy China' , deepening healthcare reform and solving the problem of 'expensive medical care' . In accordance with the World Health Organization's initiative goal of 'universal health coverage' , China is still in the process and still needs adequate, stable and sustainable government health investment to support and ensure the healthy development of health, " Zhang said.

How to Construct A LONG-TERM MECHANISM OF GOVERNMENT HEALTH INVESTMENT?

Zhang Yuhui believes that the next step is to actively adapt to the new normal of financial operation, change ideas, and explore an objective, scientific, reasonable and sustainable new financial health input mechanism. On the one hand, with the continuous development of society and the improvement of living standards, People's concept of health has changed a lot. Health needs have developed from "being able to see a doctor" to "being good at seeing a doctor" and "not getting sick" , it also puts forward higher standards and requirements for the guarantee of financial investment. The direction of financial investment should be changed from "treatment-centered" to "people's health-centered" , and the mechanism of financial investment should be set up based on health outcome index.

On the other hand, considering the process of deepening health care reform and building a "healthy China" in China, it is necessary to establish a financing and growth mechanism suitable for social and economic development, ensuring the priority of the government's health investment in the central and local budgets, and effectively addressing the problem of unbalanced and inadequate development of the health sector, provide strong support for deepening medical reform and promoting the construction of "healthy China".

"At the same time, we also need to realize that under the new normal economic environment, the long-term mechanism of government health investment in China should pay more attention to how to allocate and use funds, that is, considering how to focus the limited financial investment on the main health problems and the main influencing factors throughout the life cycle, identifying priority intervention areas and improving the input-output efficiency of financial funds, " Zhang said, in accordance with General Secretary Xi Jinping's request of "comprehensively implementing performance management" at the 19th CPC National Congress, earnestly enhance the awareness of performance management in all departments, promote the formation of "re-input and re-output, re-use and re-efficiency, re-distribution and re-supervision" of the new concept.

Enlightenment of Educational Funds Investment

How much and how much is a country's government spending on health care reasonable? With the rapid development of China's economy and society, this issue of people's livelihood has attracted more and more attention.

This is not a new topic. The reporter noted that on the issue of ensuring the stability and sustainability of government health investment, there are quite a number of views that health expenditure should be safeguarded in the same way as education expenditure, and that the proportion of government health investment in GDP or fiscal revenue should be made clear.

During the 2018 review of the draft law on basic medical care and health promotion, members of the NPC special committee suggested that legislation should be made to specify the proportion of health expenditure in GDP. However, the basic health care and Health Promotion Act, which was finally voted in the end of 2019 and came into effect on June 1,2020, only provides in principle for the financial guarantee of health care, and does not specify specific quantitative indicators.

Like health, education as a percentage of gross domestic product is a common indicator of a country's educational level.

As early as 1993, the outline for China's education reform and development issued by the State Council made it clear that the proportion of state financial expenditure on education in the gross national product would be gradually increased to 4 percent by the end of this century (2000) .

At that time, China's reform and opening up and modernization drive is entering a new stage of accelerated development, but the education cause overall relatively backward situation and economic construction does not fit. At the same time, "education funding is quite scarce" . In 1993, the national financial expenditure on education accounted for only 2.51% of GDP, far below the world average.

However, the realization of this goal is not easy, in the context of the country's limited level of economic development, the low proportion of fiscal revenue in GDP, the weak foundation of education, and so on, until 2012, after nearly 20 years of unremitting efforts, that goal was achieved.

4% , a seemingly modest figure, has propelled China's education to a historic leap. In 2012, for example, the gross enrolment ratio in kindergartens more than doubled compared with 1990, according to figures released by the Ministry of Education. At compulsory education, the gross enrolment ratio in junior high schools increased by more than 50 percent, while the gross enrolment ratio in senior high schools more than tripled, the Gross University enrolment ratio has increased almost eightfold.

After 2012, the country continued to consolidate hard-won development gains. By 2018, the national financial expenditure on education accounted for more than 4% of GDP for seven consecutive years. The highest was 4.28% in 2012 and 4.11% in 2018.

Du Yubo, a former vice-minister of education, has said that "the bottom line of 4 per cent of education expenditure should be maintained" . The state has adopted policies and regulations that not only set a 4 percent threshold, but also provide legal guarantees for the sustainability of financial investment in education.

In the Education Law implemented in 1995, it is clearly stated that "the proportion of the national financial expenditure on education to the gross national product should be gradually increased with the development of the national economy and the growth of the financial revenue" . Although the Education Act has been amended several times, this provision has remained unchanged. In 2018, the State Council issued the "opinions on further adjusting and optimizing the structure to improve the efficiency of the use of education funds, " adding another 4 percent to the target, "We should ensure that the national financial expenditure on education as a proportion of GDP is not less than 4% , and that the general public budget expenditure on education only increases year by year. ".

It is also a series of policy guarantees, nearly 30 years, China's education has not only made remarkable achievements, the overall level of development has also advanced into the ranks of the world.

As early as 2014, an assessment by the Ministry of Education showed that China's compulsory education penetration rate is higher than the average of the world's high income countries; Both the gross enrolment ratio at the senior secondary level and the gross enrolment ratio at the tertiary level are higher than the world average for middle-and high-income countries. By 2018, the above indicators have been further improved, with the gross enrolment rate in preschool education reaching 81.7% , the compulsory education rate 94.2% , the gross enrolment rate in senior secondary education 88.8% , and the gross enrolment rate in higher education 48.1% .

The change of the education cause also makes all circles of the society start to think whether the government health investment can be carried out according to the education, that is to say, the government health expenditure should make up the proportion of GDP, and increase with it.

In fact, in the decision on health reform and development issued by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council in January 1997, China put forward the following policy: "By the end of this century (2000) , we will strive for the total expenditure on health of the whole society to account for about 5% of GDP. "

This is the first time for China to use the ratio of total social health expenditure to GDP as a national control index. In 2000, the target was reached, at 5.13 per cent.

Since then, such explicit targets have not appeared in the central document.

Hard to link to GDP

At present, the specific policies and measures for government health investment are mainly reflected in the relevant documents in the field of health. Since the new medical reform, a number of policy documents for the overall level of government health investment target requirements are relatively clear.

Zhang Yuhui told reporters, for example, that "the growth rate of government health input should not be lower than the growth rate of fiscal recurrent expenditure in the same period" and that "health priority" should also be emphasized in the construction of "healthy China" , "focus on fiscal investment to ensure health needs, " he said.

"The Budget Law" also stipulates: "The preparation of general public budget expenditures at all levels should take into account all factors as a whole, and on the premise of guaranteeing the reasonable needs of basic public services, priority should be given to the key expenditures determined by the state. "

However, Zhang Yuhui said frankly that from the perspective of the Budget Law, there is no clear statement on whether health is a "key expenditure" , therefore, it is difficult to guarantee the relative priority of health-related undertakings and activities in the financial arrangement of governments at all levels. Under the pressure of local government finance, the intensity of health expenditure in some areas will be greatly affected.

"If, like education, we can set clear targets for government health spending with high binding effect, it will be a good guarantee for the stability and sustainability of government health spending, " Zhang said.

However, considering the general direction of the future financial system reform, it will be difficult to link government health investment to GDP.

In the "decision of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China on major issues in deepening reform in an all-round way" (hereinafter referred to as the decision) , adopted at the Third Plenary Session of the 18th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, it was pointed out that clearing up and regulating key expenditures is linked to the increase in fiscal revenues and expenditures or the gross output value, generally do not take the hook way.

"Therefore, there is a big debate about what kind of government health spending targets should be set in the relevant laws and regulations and relevant planning texts. Government health input as a proportion of fiscal expenditure and government health input as a proportion of GDP are commonly used indicators for analysis, but it is still difficult to use in policy practice,"Zhang Yuhui told reporters.

Therefore, Zhang Yuhui believes that there are two ways to approach this issue from the perspective of research: one is to consider the population, age structure, life expectancy, morbidity and mortality from the perspective of health outcomes, to construct a comprehensive index of health needs and take the comprehensive index of health needs as a factor to estimate the level of government health input, this paper defines the responsibility of government investment in key areas of health care, analyzes the existing gaps, and calculates the scale of government investment needed for the provision of health care services and the operation and development of health care institutions.
